\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 6. L. viscaria} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl}. 436 (1753) ({\i Viscaria viscosa} Ascherson, {\i V. vulgaris }Bernh.). Stems 15-90 cm, simple or branched above, glabrous or slightly hairy above, viscid below the upper nodes. Leaves mostly basal, linear- to ovate-lanceolate, petiolate, glabrous, usually ciliate at base. Flowers usually in 3- to 6-flowered, shortly stalked, opposite dichasia which are arranged in a lax, spike-like panicle. Calyx 6-15 mm. Petals usually dark- or pinkish-purple (rarely white), entire or emarginate. Capsule 7-10 mm.{\i  Dry, sunny slopes; somewhat calcifuge. Much of Europe, except the south-west, but absent from the islands, except Britain.} Al Au Be Br Bu Cz Da Fe Ge Gr He Hu It Ju No Po Rm Rs(N, B, C, W, E) Su Tu [Ga].
