\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 7. L. alpina} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 436 (1753) ({\i Viscaria alpina} (L.) G. Don fil.). Caespitose, glabrous, with ciliate leaf-bases; stems 5-15 cm, simple, not viscid. Basal leaves crowded, linear-subspathulate to linear; cauline usually 2 or 3 pairs, often wider. Inflorescence (6-)10- to 20-flowered, more or less capitate, rarely elongate. Calyx (3-)4-5 mm. Petal-limb pink, rarely white, bifid to about half-way. Capsule c. 4 mm; carpophore 2 mm or less. Some flowers are large and hermaphrodite, some small and usually with abortive stamens. 2n = 24.{\i  Screes and stony grassland; somewhat calcifuge. N. Europe, southwards to} 55°{\i  N.; mountains of S. & S.C. Europe,from W.C. Spain to W. Austria}. Au Br Fe Ga He Hs Is It No Rs(N, C) Su.
